{{Notice| These phaseouts were temporarily repealed by the 2018 tax law. The repeal was made permanent by the 2025 tax law.}}
The American Taxpayers Relief Act ('''ATRA''') imposes phaseouts of itemized deductions (known as Pease limitations)<ref group="note"> [[Wikipedia:Donald J. Pease | Donald J. Pease]], congressman from Ohio, drafted the limitations on itemized deductions which bear his name in 1990. See [http://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/68 26 USC § 68 - Overall limitation on itemized deductions], for the original law. </ref> and for personal exemption phaseouts (known as PEP) for taxpayers whose adjusted gross incomes surpass threshold levels. The threshold levels were the same for both phaseouts. The thresholds took effect in 2013 and were scheduled to be adjusted for future inflation.
{| class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto;width:450px;text-align:center" |+ 2017 AGI phaseout thresholds |- ! width=25%| Filing status !! width=25%| AGI threshold |- || Married filing jointly/surviving spouse ||$313,800 |- | Head of household |||$287.650 |- |Single || $261,500 |- |Married filing separate || $156,900 |}
The TCJA passed in 2017 temporarily eliminated the Pease limitation<ref>{{cite web| url=https://taxpolicycenter.org/briefing-book/how-did-tcja-change-standard-deduction-and-itemized-deductions| title=How did the TCJA change the standard deduction and itemized deductions?| publisher=Tax Policy Center| accessdate=July 5, 2025}}</ref> and the elimination was made permanent in 2025.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.thetaxadviser.com/news/2025/jun/details-of-tax-changes-in-senate-reconciliation-bill/| title=Tax provisions in the One Big Beautiful Bill Act| publisher=AICPA| accessdate=July 5, 2025}}</ref> with the [[wikipedia:One Big Beautiful Bill Act|OBBBA]]. This 2025 bill permanently removes the Sec. 68 overall limitation on itemized deductions (known as the Pease limitation) and replaces it with a new overall limitation on the tax benefit of itemized deductions. The amount of itemized deductions otherwise allowable would be reduced by 2/37 of the lesser of (1) the amount of the itemized deductions or (2) the amount of the taxpayer’s taxable income that exceeds the start of the 37% tax rate bracket.
==Pease limitations on itemized deductions (repealed)== The Pease limitation, revived by the ATRA, reduces the amount of a higher income taxpayer's itemized deductions by 3% of the amount by which the taxpayer's adjusted gross income exceeds an applicable threshold (see above table). The amount of itemized deductions reduced is limited to no more than 80%. Not all itemized deductions are subject to reduction. The following deductible expenses are excluded from the limitation:<ref name= "CHH">{{cite web| url=http://tax.cchgroup.com/downloads/files/pdfs/legislation/ATPR.pdf| title=CHH Tax Briefing: American Tax Relief Act of 2013| publisher=CCH Group| date=January 3, 2013| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627085748/https://tax.cchgroup.com/downloads/files/pdfs/legislation/ATPR.pdf| archive-date=June 27, 2017}}</ref> * Medical expenses * Investment interest * Casualty, theft, or wagering losses.
From National Council of Nonprofits:<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.councilofnonprofits.org/public-policy/pease-limitation| title=American Taxpayer Relief Act - The Pease Limitation to Itemized Deductions| publisher=National Council of Nonprofits| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208032720/http://www.councilofnonprofits.org/public-policy/pease-limitation| archive-date=February 8, 2013}}</ref> {{blockquote|For example, an individual with an adjusted gross income of $350,000 <nowiki>[in 2013; the current limit is higher]</nowiki> would be required to subtract $3,000 from their itemized deductions ($350,000 - $250,000 threshold equals $100,000 x 0.03 equals $3,000). The amount under the limit would be reduced in the example even further in the event that this taxpayer has itemized deductions of less than $15,000 because the 80 percent rule would apply.}}
Most taxpayers subject to the Pease limitation have enough itemized deductions that they take the full reduction; in particular, if they pay state income taxes, 80% of the state income tax alone is likely to be more than 3% of the excess amount. Thus the usual effect of the Pease limitation is to increase the taxpayer's [[marginal tax rate]] by about 1%. For example, in the 33% tax bracket, an extra $100 of income increases taxable income by $103, and the tax on $103 is $33.99, for a 33.99% marginal tax rate.
==PEP limitations on personal exemption== The ATRA also revives the phaseout on personal exemptions. Under the law, the total exemptions that may be claimed by a taxpayer is reduced 2% for each $2,500 ($1,250 for married filing separate) by which the taxpayer's adjusted gross income exceeds an applicable threshold.<ref name="CHH"/> For example, the 2017 personal exemption of $4050 will be reduced by 10% to $3645 if the taxpayer is $12,500 above the threshold, and will go away completely if the taxpayer is $125,000 above the threshold. Since every $10,000 of income reduces exemptions by $332 each, and increases the tax bill by $110 in a 33% bracket, the taxpayer's marginal tax rate increases by about 1% per exemption; with four exemptions, the 33% tax bracket becomes about a 37% marginal rate (and 38% with Pease).
