{{US|reason=irrelevant}}
'''{{PAGENAME}}''' is a tax imposed on a child's "certain unearned income" at the parent's [[Marginal tax rate|marginal rate]].<ref name="Kid">{{Cite web|title=26 USC 1: Tax imposed|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1)|website=Cornell Legal Information Institute|series=26 U.S. Code § 1(g)}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|"'''Unearned income defined.''' Unearned income is generally all income other than salaries, wages, and other amounts received as pay for work actually performed. It includes taxable interest, dividends, capital gains (including capital gain distributions), the taxable part of social security and pension payments, certain distributions from trusts, and unemployment compensation. Unearned income includes amounts produced by assets your child obtained with earned income (such as interest on a savings account into which you deposited wages)."<ref name="Pub929" />|group="note"}}
The term is found in the title of "''IRS Topic No. 553 Tax on a Child's Investment and Other Unearned Income (Kiddie Tax)''", but not in any other IRS publication.<ref name="Topic553">{{Cite web|title=Topic No. 553 Tax on a Child's Investment and Other Unearned Income (Kiddie Tax)|url=https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc553|website=Internal Revenue Service}}</ref><ref group="note">You won’t find the term "kiddie tax" in Publication 929 ({{Cite web|title=Publication 929 - Tax Rules for Children and Dependents.|url=https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/p929.pdf|website=Internal Revenue Service}}) nor in the instructions for Form 8615, Tax for Certain Children Who Have Unearned Income ({{Cite web|title=Instructions for Form 8615|url=https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i8615|website=Internal Revenue Service}}).</ref>
'''Background:''' "In 1986, Congress enacted the 'kiddie tax' as a response to parental abuse of tax rates. Some parents were transferring large amounts of unearned income, such as dividend and capital gains proceeds, to their children’s accounts to ensure taxation at the children’s lower tax rates."<ref>{{Cite web|date=May 23, 2006|title=The Real Effect of the “Kiddie Tax” Change|url=https://www.finance.senate.gov/chairmans-news/the-real-effect-of-the-kiddie-tax-change|website=United States Senate Committee on Finance}}</ref> Since then, the law has been modified multiple times. ==The kiddie tax in general== There are two rules that may affect the tax and reporting of the investment income of certain children:<ref name="Topic553" /> #If the child's interest, [[dividend]]s and other unearned income total more than $2,700 in 2025 or 2026 (twice the basic standard deduction for a dependent minor of $1,350, indexed for inflation<ref group="note">The basic standard deduction is indexed for inflation. The unearned income limit is twice that amount. Source: [{{{url|https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/63}}} 26 USC 63:(c)(4)] and [{{{url|https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1}}} 26 USC 1:(g)(4)(A)]</ref>), it may be subject to a specific tax on the unearned income of certain children. #If the child's interest and dividend income (including capital gain distributions) total less than $13,500 (10 times the basic standard deduction of $1,350), the child's parent may be able to elect to include that income on the parent's return rather than file a return for the child. This may result in paying more tax than having the child file a tax return. (See [https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-8814-parents-election-to-report-childs-interest-and-dividends Form 8814] and [https://www.irs.gov/publications/p929 Publication 929].) The following characterizes the kiddie tax: * Applies if the child is < 24 and a full time student (lower ages if not), and has more than $2,700 in unearned income for 2025 or 2026 *Anything over $2,700 in unearned income is taxed at the tax rate for the parents *Kiddie tax is calculated on [https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-8615 Form 8615] and paid on child's return *The standard deduction for a child who can be claimed as a dependent is the greater of **$1,350 for 2025 or 2026 (indexed for inflation) **earned income plus $450 for 2025, $450 for 2026 (indexed for inflation) but not more than the regular standard deduction amount, generally $15,000 for 2025, $16,100 for 2026 (indexed for inflation) Note that by gifting appreciated securities to a child, you can avoid at most $405 ($2,700 &times; 0.15) in 2026 (if in the 15% [[Capital gains distribution|Long Term Capital Gains]] (LTCG) bracket), or $633 ($2,700 &times; 0.238) (if in the 20% LTCG + 3.8% [[ACA net investment income tax|Net Investment Income Tax]] (NIIT) brackets).
==Taxation of children with no earned income== If the children have no [[earned income]] then: *The child (if a dependent) gets a Standard Deduction of $1,350 *This has the effect of: **The first $1,350 of unearned income is untaxed **The next $1,350 is taxed at the child's rate ***0% for [[qualified dividend]] (QDI) and long term capital gain (LTCG) ***10% for Interest and non-QDI **Anything beyond that is taxed at the parents' tax rate ===Examples=== '''Example 1:''' Your child has no other income than $1,000 of LTCG from stock you gave him. His standard deduction is $1,350 and his taxable income is zero. You save $150 (15% of $1,000) in the 15% LTCG bracket compared to selling it yourself.
'''Example 2:''' Your child has no other income than $3,000 of LTCG from stock you gave her. Her standard deduction is $1,350 and her taxable income is $1,650. In 2025, since her unearned income is over $2,700, the last $300 is taxed at the parents' rate; if the parents pay 15% tax on LTCG, the tax is $45.
'''Example 3:''' (2025 optimal [[tax gain harvesting]]) Your child has no other income than $2,700 of LTCG from stock you gave her. Her standard deduction is $1,350 and her taxable income is $1,350. In 2025, since her unearned income is exactly $2,700, she has $0 taxed at the parents' rate. ==Taxation of children with earned income== If the children have earned income then: *The standard deduction is $1,300 for 2024, $1,350 for 2025, or (earned income + $450 for 2024, $450 for 2025) whichever is larger, but not more than the normal standard deduction of $14,600 for 2024, $15,000 for 2025 (indexed for inflation) for a single person. ===Examples=== '''Example 1:''' A child has $200 of earned income. His standard deduction is $1,350. With $500 of ordinary unearned income (interest, short-term capital gains (STCG), and non-QDI) and $1,350 of tax advantaged unearned income (QDI and LTCG), his total income is $2,000, and his taxable income is $650. Under the "income stacking rules" of the Qualified Dividends and Capital Gain Tax worksheet, all of his taxable income is tax advantaged, and his tax is $0.
'''Example 2:''' A child has $1,200 of earned income. Her standard deduction is $1,650 ($1,200 + $450). With $500 of ordinary unearned income (interest, STCG, and non-QDI) and $1,400 of tax advantaged unearned income (QDI and LTCG) her total income is $3,050, and her taxable income is $1,400. Under the "income stacking rules" of the Qualified Dividends and Capital Gain Tax worksheet, the taxable income consists of $50 of ordinary income ($500 - $450) and $1,350 of tax advantaged income. Her tax will be $5 (10% of $50). ==Form 8514 - parents' election to report child's interest and dividends== "You may be able to elect to include your child's interest and dividend income (including capital gain distributions) on your tax return. If you do, your child won't have to file a return."<ref name="Pub929">{{Cite web|title=Publication 929, Tax Rules for Children and Dependents|url=https://www.irs.gov/publications/p929|access-date=September 20, 2021|website=Internal Revenue Service|series=Parents' Election To Report Child's Interest and Dividends (Form 8814)}}</ref>
Figure 1 shows the conditions which allow you to attach [https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-8814 Form 8814] to your tax return (numbers are from 2020, but otherwise the rules are the same): {| border="1" |+'''Figure 1. Can You Include Your Child's Income on Your Tax Return?<ref name="Pub929" />''' |- ||[[File:IRS Publication 929 Figure1.gif|alt=Figure 1. Can You Include Your Child's Income on Your Tax Return?|link=https://www.bogleheads.org/wiki/File:IRS_Publication_929_Figure1.gif]] |} ==Form 8615 - tax for certain children who have unearned income== "If your child's interest, dividends, and other unearned income total more than $2,600, and you don't or can't use Form 8814 to include your child's income on your return, your child will use [https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-8615 Form 8615] to figure their tax. Attach the completed Form 8615 to your child's Form 1040 or 1040-NR."<ref name="Pub929" />
Figure 2 shows the conditions which allow you to attach Form 8615 (numbers are from 2020, but otherwise the rules are the same) {| border="1" |+'''Figure 2. Does Your Child Have To Use Form 8615 To Figure Their Tax?<ref name="Pub929" />''' |- ||[[File:IRS Publication 929 Figure2.gif|alt=Figure 1. Can You Include Your Child's Income on Your Tax Return?|link=https://www.bogleheads.org/wiki/File:IRS_Publication_929_Figure2.gif]] |}
==State kiddie tax== Some states have similar rules for taxing the unearned income of children; California is one of them.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tax Computation for Certain Children with Unearned Income (2019)|url=https://www.ftb.ca.gov/forms/2019/2019-3800.pdf|website=Franchise Tax Board, State of California}}</ref>
