Known as the One Big Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA), [https://www.congress.gov/bill/119th-congress/house-bill/1 H.R.1 - 119th Congress (2025-2026)] modifies US taxation and became law on July 4, 2025. '''{{PAGENAME}}''' provides an overview of changes made in this Act.

Although the law has changed, the IRS tax forms may not have been updated to reflect these changes.

For example, [https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-announces-no-changes-to-individual-information-returns-or-withholding-tables-for-2025-under-the-one-big-beautiful-bill-act IRS announces no changes to individual information returns or withholding tables for 2025 under the One, Big, Beautiful Bill Act] currently describes changes the IRS will ''not'' make for tax year 2025, but remains silent on what actually will be implemented.

Tax law changes are summarized in: 

* {{Cite web|last=Kitces|first=Michael|date=July 16, 2025|title=Breaking Down The “One Big Beautiful Bill Act”: Impact Of New Laws On Tax Planning|url=https://www.kitces.com/blog/obbba-one-big-beautiful-bill-act-tax-planning-salt-cap-senior-deduction-qbi-deduction-tax-cut-and-jobs-act-tcja-amt-trump-accounts/|access-date=August 31, 2025|website=Kitces}}

The ''External links'' section [[#External links|below]] has related articles which describe these changes from a different perspective.

==Tax estimation tools==
{{Main | Tax estimation tools}}

It can be challenging to understand how these changes will affect you. Instead of waiting for tax software to be released at the end of the year, tax estimation tools can help you prepare for these changes during the ''current'' year.

A list of the [[Tax estimation tools#Latest tax year available |latest tax year available]] identifies which tools have been updated to incorporate the July 4, 2025 changes (at least to the extent the IRS is expected to implement them).

